Solve for $x$: $3(2x - 5) - 2(x - 1) = 3$

Solution:

$3(2x - 5) - 2(x - 1) = 3$
$\therefore 3 \times 2x + 3 \times (-5) - 2 \times x - 2 \times (-1) = 3$ {expanding brackets}
$\therefore 6x - 15 - 2x + 2 = 3$
$\therefore 4x - 13 = 3$ {collecting like terms}
$\therefore 4x - 13 + 13 = 3 + 13$ {adding 13 to both sides}
$\therefore 4x = 16$
$\therefore x = 4$ {dividing both sides by 4}

