Solve for $x$: $\frac{x}{2} = \frac{3 + x}{5}$

Solution:

$\frac{x}{2} = \frac{3 + x}{5}$ has LCD $= 10$

$\therefore \frac{x}{2} \times \frac{5}{5} = \frac{2}{2} \times \left(\frac{3 + x}{5}\right)$ {to create a common denominator}

$\therefore 5x = 2(3 + x)$ {equating numerators}
$\therefore 5x = 6 + 2x$ {expanding brackets}
$\therefore 5x - 2x = 6 + 2x - 2x$ {subtracting $2x$ from both sides}
$\therefore 3x = 6$
$\therefore x = 2$ {dividing both sides by 3}

Solve for $x$: $\frac{4}{x} = \frac{3}{4}$

Solution:

$\frac{4}{x} = \frac{3}{4}$ has LCD $= 4x$

$\therefore \frac{4}{x} \times \frac{4}{4} = \frac{3}{4} \times \frac{x}{x}$ {to create a common denominator}

$\therefore 16 = 3x$ {equating numerators}
$\therefore x = \frac{16}{3}$ {dividing both sides by 3}

Solve for $x$: $\frac{2x + 1}{3 - x} = \frac{3}{4}$

Solution:

$\frac{2x + 1}{3 - x} = \frac{3}{4}$ has LCD $= 4(3 - x)$

$\therefore \frac{4}{4} \times \left(\frac{2x + 1}{3 - x}\right) = \frac{3}{4} \times \left(\frac{3 - x}{3 - x}\right)$ {to create a common denominator}

$\therefore 4(2x + 1) = 3(3 - x)$ {equating numerators}
$\therefore 8x + 4 = 9 - 3x$ {expanding the brackets}
$\therefore 8x + 4 + 3x = 9 - 3x + 3x$ {adding $3x$ to both sides}
$\therefore 11x + 4 = 9$
$\therefore 11x + 4 - 4 = 9 - 4$ {subtracting 4 from both sides}
$\therefore 11x = 5$
$\therefore x = \frac{5}{11}$ {dividing both sides by 11}
